      <p>Sotol and yucca (on right) growing
          on the canyon rim near Hinds Cave. Sotol usually blooms in the spring,
          but in dry years it waits for rain and blooms when it can. Sotol (Dasylirion)was
          a very useful resource. Its strong leaves were trimmed of their thorns
          (or not) and used to weave mats or separated into fibers for making
          cord and sandal straps. Its dried stalk was used as a lightweight wood
          and as fuel. And its leaf base or heart was baked and eaten, especially
          during the Late Archaic period at Hinds Cave. Yucca was valued mainly
          as a source of tough fibers that come with a built-in needle (the thorn
      tip). TAMU Anthropology archives. </p>
